  "prompt": "Why are all the Hindu mythological characters such as Ram, Raavan, Laxman, Arjun written as Rama, Ravana and so on in English books? Who has mandated the extra 'a'?",
  "response": "The addition of the final 'a' in transliterating Sanskrit and other Indian language names is primarily due to linguistic and scholarly conventions rather than a single mandated rule. Here are some key reasons:\n\n1. Sanskrit Grammatical Tradition:\n- In Sanskrit, most masculine names end with a consonant\n- Adding 'a' helps represent the masculine nominative case\n- Example: \"Ram\" becomes \"Rama\" to reflect grammatical structure\n\n2. Academic Transliteration Standards:\n- Scholars and linguists developed standardized transliteration systems\n- IAST (International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration) is one such widely accepted system\n- These systems aim to preserve phonetic accuracy\n\n3. Pronunciation Representation:\n- The 'a' helps English speakers pronounce the name closer to its original sound\n- Without the 'a', names might be mispronounced\n\n4. Historical Scholarly Practices:\n- 19th and early 20th-century Orientalist scholars popularized this convention\n- Their translations and works established this practice\n\n5. Consistency in Academic and Literary Works:\n- Once established, the convention became widely adopted\n- Helps maintain uniformity across scholarly publications\n\nIt's not a legally mandated rule but a scholarly and linguistic convention that has become widely accepted.",
